🐳 1. Docker Basics

docker --version – Displays installed Docker version
docker info – Shows Docker system info
docker help – Lists all Docker commands

📦 2. Working with Images
docker pull <image> – Download image from Docker Hub
docker images – View all downloaded images
docker rmi <image> – Delete an image
docker build -t <name> . – Build image from Dockerfile


🧱 3. Working with Containers
docker run <image> – Run a container
docker run --name <name> <image> – Run container with a specific name
docker ps – List running containers
docker ps -a – List all containers (running + stopped)
docker stop <container> – Stop a running container
docker start <container> – Start a stopped container
docker restart <container> – Restart a container
docker rm <container> – Remove a container
docker exec -it <container> bash – Get shell access into a container
docker logs <container> – View container logs
###########################################
docker run --name web01 -d -p 9080:80 nginx     >>>>>port mapping available on web
docker inspect <name>                           >>> gives info including ip



##############

🗃️ 4. Volumes (Data Management)
docker volume create <name> – Create a volume
docker volume ls – List all volumes
docker volume inspect <name> – Show volume details
docker volume rm <name> – Remove a volume


🌐 5. Networking
docker network ls – List Docker networks
docker network create <name> – Create a custom network
docker network connect <network> <container> – Connect a container to a network
docker network inspect <name> – Show network details


📄 6. Dockerfile & Image Management
docker build -t <name> . – Build an image from a Dockerfile
docker tag <image> <repo>:<tag> – Tag/rename an image
docker push <repo>:<tag> – Push image to Docker Hub
docker login – Log in to Docker Hub


🧹 7. Cleanup Commands
docker container prune – Remove all stopped containers
docker image prune – Remove unused/dangling images
docker system prune -a – Remove unused data (images, containers, volumes, etc.)



📦 8. Docker Compose (for multi-container apps)
docker-compose up – Start services defined in docker-compose.yml
docker-compose up -d – Start services in detached mode
docker-compose down – Stop and remove services/containers
docker-compose build – Build services
docker-compose logs – View service logs
docker-compose exec <service> <cmd> – Run a command in a service container
